    'html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>You can buy the highest-purity peptide on the market and render it useless in a week through improper storage. Peptides are proteins, and proteins are fragile. Heat denatures them. Light degrades them. Moisture triggers reactions that break them down. The good news is that proper storage is straightforward once you know the rules.</p>

<h2>Unreconstituted Peptides (Lyophilized Powder)</h2>

<p>Lyophilized (freeze-dried) peptides are the most stable form. The water has been removed, which eliminates most degradation pathways. In this form, peptides are surprisingly durable if stored correctly.</p>

<p><strong>Freezer storage (-20C / -4F):</strong> The gold standard for long-term storage. At freezer temperatures, lyophilized peptides remain stable for 12-24 months or longer depending on the specific sequence. Most suppliers ship peptides at ambient temperature because the lyophilized form tolerates short transit periods, but once received, get them in the freezer.</p>

<p><strong>Refrigerator storage (2-8C / 36-46F):</strong> Acceptable for medium-term storage of 3-6 months. If you plan to use a peptide within a few months, the refrigerator is fine. For anything longer, use the freezer.</p>

<p><strong>Room temperature:</strong> Lyophilized peptides tolerate room temperature for days to weeks without major degradation, but it's not ideal for storage beyond transit. Higher temperatures accelerate any trace moisture-driven reactions.</p>

<p><strong>Light protection:</strong> Keep vials in their original packaging or wrap in foil. UV light causes photodegradation of certain amino acid residues (tryptophan, tyrosine, phenylalanine). Even ambient room lighting causes slow degradation over weeks. A box in the freezer solves both temperature and light requirements.</p>

<h2>Reconstituted Peptides (In Solution)</h2>

<p>Once you add bacteriostatic water to a lyophilized peptide, the stability rules change dramatically. Water reintroduces hydrolysis and oxidation pathways that were eliminated during freeze-drying.</p>

<p><strong>Always refrigerate:</strong> Reconstituted peptides must be stored at 2-8C (36-46F). Never freeze a reconstituted peptide. Freezing causes ice crystal formation that can physically damage the peptide structure, and the freeze-thaw cycle is one of the most destructive things you can do to a protein in solution.</p>

<p><strong>28-day rule:</strong> Bacteriostatic water's benzyl alcohol preservative prevents bacterial growth for approximately 28 days. After that, contamination risk increases even if the solution looks clear. Most practitioners recommend discarding reconstituted peptides after 28 days regardless of remaining volume.</p>

<p><strong>Some peptides degrade faster:</strong> Not all peptides have the same stability in solution. GHK-Cu and BPC-157 are relatively stable and may last the full 28 days. More complex peptides with multiple disulfide bonds or sensitive sequences may lose potency within 2-3 weeks. When in doubt, reconstitute smaller amounts more frequently rather than one large batch.</p>

<h2>The Enemies of Peptide Stability</h2>

<p><strong>Heat:</strong> The primary destroyer. Every 10C increase in temperature roughly doubles the rate of chemical degradation. A peptide stored at 37C (body temperature) degrades 4-8x faster than one at 4C (refrigerator). Leaving a reconstituted peptide on a bathroom counter for an afternoon in summer can measurably reduce potency.</p>

<p><strong>Light:</strong> Ultraviolet and visible light provide energy that drives photochemical reactions in peptide bonds and aromatic amino acids. Amber vials offer some protection. Aluminum foil wrapping is better. A closed box in the refrigerator is best.</p>

<p><strong>Oxygen:</strong> Methionine and cysteine residues are particularly susceptible to oxidation. Each time you puncture a vial's stopper, a small amount of air enters. This is generally not a problem over 28 days of normal use, but leaving a vial with a partially pulled stopper or transferring peptide between open containers accelerates oxidation.</p>

<p><strong>pH shifts:</strong> Bacteriostatic water has a near-neutral pH that most peptides tolerate well. Mixing peptides with acidic or basic solutions can cause rapid denaturation. Don't mix peptides with anything other than bacteriostatic water (or sterile water for single-use, though BAC water is preferred for multi-dose vials).</p>

<h2>Can You Freeze Reconstituted Peptides?</h2>

<p>This question comes up constantly, and the answer is: it depends, but generally avoid it. Standard home freezers create large, slow-growing ice crystals that physically disrupt protein structure. Flash-freezing in liquid nitrogen followed by storage at -80C is used in research labs and preserves protein structure, but home freezers don't achieve this.</p>

<p>If you must freeze a reconstituted peptide (perhaps you reconstituted too much), aliquot it into single-use portions before freezing. This way you only thaw each portion once. Never freeze, thaw, and refreeze the same solution. Each freeze-thaw cycle causes cumulative damage.</p>

<p>The better approach: only reconstitute what you'll use within 28 days. If a vial contains more peptide than you need for one cycle, reconstitute half and keep the rest as powder in the freezer.</p>

<h2>Shipping and Travel</h2>

<p>Lyophilized peptides can handle 2-5 days of shipping at ambient temperature without significant degradation. Most suppliers ship with cold packs in summer as an extra precaution, but the powder form is resilient enough for standard transit.</p>

<p>Reconstituted peptides require cold chain maintenance during travel. An insulated bag with an ice pack keeps temperatures appropriate for several hours. For air travel, keep reconstituted peptides in a small insulated pouch in your carry-on (checked baggage holds can reach temperature extremes). TSA allows medically necessary injectable solutions.</p>

<p>For extended travel, bring unreconstituted vials and a vial of BAC water. Reconstitute at your destination. This eliminates cold chain concerns entirely.</p>

<h2>Quick Storage Reference</h2>

<ul>
<li><strong>Lyophilized powder, long-term:</strong> Freezer (-20C), dark, sealed. Stable 12-24+ months.</li>
<li><strong>Lyophilized powder, short-term:</strong> Refrigerator (2-8C), dark. Stable 3-6 months.</li>
<li><strong>Reconstituted with BAC water:</strong> Refrigerator only. Use within 28 days. Never freeze.</li>
<li><strong>General rules:</strong> Keep dark. Keep cold. Keep sealed. Don't shake.</li>
</ul>

<p>Proper storage is not complicated, but it is non-negotiable. A $100 vial of peptide stored carelessly becomes a $100 vial of degraded amino acids. The few minutes spent storing correctly protect both your investment and your results.</p>
